  "prompt": "What is the climate of California's coastal regions, and how does it compare to the climate in Oklahoma?",
  "response": "California's coastal regions have a Mediterranean climate characterized by mild, wet winters and warm, dry summers. Temperatures are moderated by the Pacific Ocean, resulting in relatively stable, cool temperatures year-round. Average coastal temperatures typically range from the 50s to 70s Fahrenheit.\n\nIn contrast, Oklahoma has a humid subtropical climate with more extreme temperature variations. Oklahoma experiences hot summers, often reaching over 90\u00b0F, and cold winters with temperatures that can drop below freezing. Oklahoma also has more significant seasonal changes and is prone to severe weather like thunderstorms and tornadoes.\n\nKey differences include:\n1. Temperature range: California coastal areas have more consistent temperatures\n2. Precipitation patterns: California has dry summers, while Oklahoma has more distributed rainfall\n3. Weather extremes: Oklahoma experiences more dramatic weather events\n4. Humidity: Oklahoma is generally more humid than California's coastal regions\n\nThe Pacific Ocean significantly influences California's coastal climate, creating a more temperate environment compared to Oklahoma's more continental climate.",
